======================================================================
2D vs 1D Clustering Tension — Diagnostic Analysis
======================================================================
  N = 19
  Observed: 1D R = 0.5052, 2D R_sphere = 0.5619
  ϖ-i correlation = -0.1167

  H0_full (both ϖ,i uniform):  median R = 0.2051
                                 p = 0.000220

  H0_ibin (ϖ random in i-bins): median R = 0.3485
                                  p = 0.006180

  H0_iboot (ϖ random, i fixed):  median R = 0.3489
                                  p = 0.006260

  H0_1d (ϖ uniform):             median R = 0.1924
                                  p = 0.005660

--- Decomposition: equatorial (ϖ) vs axial (i) ---
  Observed R_xy = 0.4762  (equatorial, ϖ-dependent)
  Observed R_z  = +0.2983  (axial, i-dependent)
  Null median R_xy (ϖ random) = 0.1813
  Null median R_z  (full unif) = -0.0005
  p(R_xy | i fixed) = 0.007040
  p(R_z  | uniform) = 0.023480

--- Survey-weighted ϖ clustering test ---
  Mean detection prob  = 0.970
  Min detection prob   = 0.424 (highest-i object)
  Observed R (weighted)= 0.5052
  Null median R (weighted) = 0.1953
  p(survey-weighted)   = 0.006560

======================================================================
DIAGNOSIS: Why is the 2D signal stronger than 1D?
======================================================================

  1D Rayleigh (ϖ only):      p = 0.0057
  2D spherical (independence):p = 0.000220
  2D (ϖ random, i fixed):     p = 0.006260
  2D equatorial (R_xy):        p = 0.007040
  2D axial (R_z):              p = 0.023480

The 2D signal is stronger because BOTH ϖ and i deviate from uniformity.
R_z = +0.2983 (p_z = 0.023480) reflects the survey-biased i distribution,
NOT intrinsic clustering. The equatorial component R_xy = 0.4762
(which isolates the ϖ structure) has p = 0.007040 — comparable to 1D p = 0.005660.

Moreover, the detection probability depends on i (surveys are latitude-
limited). This creates an observed ϖ-i correlation through selection, not
through dynamics. The survey-weighted ϖ test gives p = 0.006560 —
comparable to the unweighted 1D result.

WARNING: The equatorial component p = 0.007040 is significant even
after accounting for the i-marginal distribution. This means the ϖ
clustering cannot be fully explained by i-dependent detection alone.
However, at N=19, a more sophisticated survey model (full 6D orbit
integration through survey footprints) is needed to rule out residual
selection effects — consistent with the paper's Model B analysis.
